            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/27343",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Debugging your example I get:\n\n{code}\n$date = new Zend_Date(mktime(22, 0, 0, 10, 25, 2008));\n{code}\n\nThe date object contains\n{code}\n2008-10-25T22:00:00+00:00\n{code}\nwhich is correct... now you set the timezone\n{code}\n$date->setTimezone('Europe\/Berlin');\n{code}\nand the object changes to\n{code}\n2008-10-26T00:00:00+02:00\n{code}\nwhich is correct because we are in summertime on this date so GMT+2\nNow you add one day\n{code}\n$date->add(1, Zend_Date::DAY);\n{code}\nbut there is a change from summer to wintertime... so the object changes to\n{code}\n2008-10-26T23:00:00+01:00\n{code}\nbecause this day has only 23 hours, but also the zone changes to GMT+1\nSubstracting one second makes no difference\n{code}\n$date->sub(1, Zend_Date::SECOND);\n{code}\nas the zone does not change on 22-23h.\n{code}\n2008-10-26T22:59:59+01:00\n{code}\n\nI see no problem at all.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2008-12-16T01:09:25.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2008-12-16T01:09:25.000+0000"
                }
            ]
